Steve Pope (spp@bob.eecs.berkeley.edu) wrote:
: In article <2vnrln$3hv@mycroft.rand.org> jim@acm.org writes:

: | This is the d'Agapeyeff Cipher [...]
: | Quite a few people have had a go at it [...]
: | My current theory is that he was trying to execute a Mirabeau cipher 
: | (like a checkerboard with nulls) but botched the encryption in some 
: | unknown way.

: Ummmm.... since when does creating a cipher that resists attack
: constitute "botching the encryption" ??

: Steve

The encryption is botched if the recipient cannot decrypt the message.  In
this case not even the message's originator could decrypt it.  Mind you,
a botched encryption does resist attack, all right, but not always.  
Sometimes the cryptanalyst has more success than the legitimate recipient.
